{
  "doc_id": "20670",
  "text": "Cambial cell division in Arabidopsis is controlled by a protein ligand receptor complex [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . The ligand is the small CLE41 protein, produced in the phloem and transported into the cambium, where it interacts with the PXY receptor to stimulate cambium cell division [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Recently, constitutive expression of aspen orthologs of the ligand and receptor in transgenic poplar trees resulted in highly pleiotropic and negative effects on growth and tissue organization [CITATION_7] . However, when the ligand and receptor were simultaneously upregulated in their native tissue domains employing tissue specific promoters, not only that the negative effects were completely mitigated, but also the double transgenic plants showed a nearly double increases in wood production (Figure 2A) .",
